00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:53.731
When we think about a dot QMD, which is what we're going to focus on for the remainder

00:37:53.731 --> 00:37:56.971
of today, a QMD file is plain text.

00:37:56.971 --> 00:38:01.090
So you have metadata with choosing a format or choosing an engine.

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:04.971
Obviously, we can choose Knitter and stick with R or we can choose Jupyter and do

00:38:04.971 --> 00:38:07.451
something in Julia or Python.

00:38:07.451 --> 00:38:09.490
Then we execute some code.

00:38:09.490 --> 00:38:11.011
So we've chosen our format.

00:38:11.011 --> 00:38:13.571
We've got some code in R or Python we want to execute.

00:38:13.571 --> 00:38:17.291
We go through here and we group by summarize on empty cars.

00:38:17.291 --> 00:38:20.890
Everyone's favorite data set that's kind of built in or a boring little data set.

00:38:22.131 --> 00:38:24.170
But then we can also add text to this.

00:38:24.170 --> 00:38:28.811
So rather than just executing code, we can add Markdown text and do things like adding

00:38:28.811 --> 00:38:33.770
alternative text to images or bolding the text or italicizing text or adding headers or

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:35.050
subsections.

00:38:35.090 --> 00:38:40.330
But overall, you can still read this and it's plain text format, but it's indicating this

00:38:40.330 --> 00:38:45.090
is the Markdown or the markup to generate an output format in bold or italics or other

00:38:45.090 --> 00:38:45.610
things.

00:38:47.971 --> 00:38:52.531
The metadata or that YAML at the top is what's controlling the overall rendering

00:38:52.531 --> 00:38:53.330
process.

00:38:53.330 --> 00:38:55.811
So this tells you what is the output format I want to do?

00:38:55.811 --> 00:38:58.291
What kind of table of contents do I want to do?

00:38:58.291 --> 00:39:01.770
What are all the different things that I want to do across the entire document as it

00:39:01.770 --> 00:39:02.770
goes?

00:39:02.770 --> 00:39:07.411
And again, this can affect things like the code or just the content, the rendering process

00:39:07.411 --> 00:39:09.011
or how it appears.

00:39:09.011 --> 00:39:11.770
And it's usually read across by all the different components.

00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:15.811
So it interacts with Pandoc and interacts with Cordo and interacts with Knitter and

00:39:15.811 --> 00:39:17.851
affects all the different processes over time.

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:23.330
What the YAML actually looks like is you'd have something like this.

00:39:23.330 --> 00:39:27.851
It's indicated with three dashes at the top and you do something like, what is the title

00:39:27.851 --> 00:39:28.811
of my document?

00:39:28.811 --> 00:39:31.930
And then most importantly, choosing a format.

00:39:31.930 --> 00:39:36.210
Coming from our markdown, you might have been familiar with the output.

00:39:36.210 --> 00:39:40.571
Here, we're always going to indicate that as format and then we can do something like

00:39:40.571 --> 00:39:45.851
HTML, add a table of contents and say that it's true, and then add code folding.

00:39:45.851 --> 00:39:49.610
So while the code is available, it's hidden behind a little details tag that can be

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:51.691
opened or closed.

00:39:51.691 --> 00:39:55.851
But most importantly, you have three dashes at the top, three dashes at the bottom,

00:39:55.851 --> 00:40:01.170
and that indicates the opening and closing of your document as you move forward.

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:04.370
The markdown components is based, again, on Pandoc.

00:40:04.370 --> 00:40:08.571
Pandoc is ultimately the tool that's behind the scenes being converting it out to other

00:40:08.571 --> 00:40:09.811
formats.

00:40:09.811 --> 00:40:13.851
And Pandoc markdown is very rich.

00:40:13.851 --> 00:40:20.650
So you can have, you know, not just the most basic markdown, but really, really kind of

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:24.851
expansive markdown that allows you to do layout and kind of structuring of the document

00:40:24.851 --> 00:40:26.571
overall.

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:32.650
So it's based on John Gruber's markdown syntax, and it has the importance of being plain text

00:40:32.650 --> 00:40:35.531
so that it's easy to read and easy to write.

00:40:35.531 --> 00:40:39.170
And when you check it into something like version control, your diffs are very easy

00:40:39.170 --> 00:40:40.650
to also read and write.

00:40:40.650 --> 00:40:45.451
So rather than a whole document changing if you change one or two lines, the structure

00:40:45.451 --> 00:40:50.050
is just where you can see the diffs and the different portions that are changed in source

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:53.291
control as well.

00:40:53.291 --> 00:40:57.770
Markdown might do things like italics or bold or superscript, strikethrough, or even

00:40:57.770 --> 00:41:00.411
displaying verbatim code.

00:41:00.411 --> 00:41:05.210
So this allows you to write, again, like lots of different markup about what you're doing.

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:09.650
And while you're looking at even just the plain text, you can also kind of imagine what

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:11.890
that's going to look like in the output format.

00:41:11.890 --> 00:41:17.930
And again, if you're using RStudio with the visual editor mode, you can also render, essentially

00:41:18.090 --> 00:41:23.370
preview what all the different parts are in real time by switching from source mode to

00:41:23.370 --> 00:41:24.370
visual mode.

00:41:24.370 --> 00:41:30.490
Importantly, there's also the idea of headers in Markdown and in Pandock Markdown.

00:41:30.490 --> 00:41:35.531
So these allow you to break up a document by adding pound signs in front of text and

00:41:35.531 --> 00:41:40.651
say, this is a head section, and then you can build up subsections within each of those.

00:41:40.651 --> 00:41:48.211
So you can write out your headers and do overall complex kind of layouts of your document.

00:41:48.211 --> 00:41:50.930
As for code, and there was a good question I saw in the chat.

00:41:50.930 --> 00:41:55.490
So with Knitter, you can execute R code and Python code together.

00:41:55.490 --> 00:41:59.091
That would be using reticulate, and that's an important idea.

00:41:59.091 --> 00:42:02.170
You can merge them both into the same document.

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:03.651
So here I have a code chunk.

00:42:03.651 --> 00:42:09.651
It's just executing R, but via reticulate, I could execute R and Python code together.

00:42:09.651 --> 00:42:14.211
If I wanted to use Python alone, I can use Jupyter as my engine, and R doesn't have to

00:42:14.211 --> 00:42:16.050
be involved in that process.

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:19.490
So you don't have to go to a Python colleague and tell them, hey, you know, there's this

00:42:19.490 --> 00:42:24.091
cool tool we could collaborate on, but you have to install R, and you have to use R packages

00:42:24.091 --> 00:42:25.251
to manage it.

00:42:25.251 --> 00:42:30.410
They can just use it in their native language without having to install anything else.

00:42:30.410 --> 00:42:34.011
We're going to talk a little bit more about what code chunks actually build up with in

00:42:34.011 --> 00:42:36.651
the second half of today.

00:42:36.651 --> 00:42:40.610
But you might notice that there's this hash pipe syntax at the top indicating the chunk

00:42:40.610 --> 00:42:46.451
options as opposed to putting them into the chunk label where they might have been before.

00:42:46.451 --> 00:42:49.930
But regardless, you have this ability to, in a Horto document, just like I'm working

00:42:49.930 --> 00:42:54.091
on today, write code that generates outputs.

00:42:54.091 --> 00:43:01.730
And it can do more than just R, and you can actually have, you know, insertion of graphics

00:43:01.730 --> 00:43:04.470
in Matplotlib or using NumPy.

00:43:04.470 --> 00:43:09.110
So again, we can mix R and Python together in Knitter with Reticulate, or we could have

00:43:09.110 --> 00:43:14.430
a Python pure document that's using just Jupyter as its engine and doesn't have to have R in

00:43:14.430 --> 00:43:15.670
the full process.

00:43:15.670 --> 00:43:21.030
So it's more than just R, and you're able to collaborate with your colleagues.

