00:57:48.591 --> 00:57:52.831
So ultimately, again, we covered a little bit of the high details, but went through

00:57:52.831 --> 00:57:53.831
them pretty quickly.

00:57:53.831 --> 00:57:57.591
So now we're going to spend a bit more time talking about how to actually do things as

00:57:57.591 --> 00:58:00.890
opposed to just about what you can do.

00:58:00.890 --> 00:58:04.311
So we're going to talk about Cordo documents and mainly about this anatomy.

00:58:04.750 --> 00:58:07.670
We're going to go through YAML, talk about the different ways you can create formats.

00:58:07.670 --> 00:58:13.231
We're going to talk about markdown and text, and creating that over to the documents that

00:58:13.231 --> 00:58:15.790
you're rendering out, and then using code.

00:58:15.790 --> 00:58:21.351
So using things like Knitter or Jupyter to execute R or Python and Julia code.

00:58:21.351 --> 00:58:25.510
You add all these things together, and you have those beautiful, powerful, useful outputs,

00:58:25.510 --> 00:58:28.231
and again, you're creating them with a plain text input.

00:58:28.231 --> 00:58:33.231
So you don't have to write all the different things while you can embed raw CSS and raw

00:58:33.430 --> 00:58:36.270
LaTeX and all these other different things into it.

00:58:36.270 --> 00:58:43.231
Cordo provides a lot of power to do all that just through what's built into Cordo.

00:58:43.231 --> 00:58:47.351
This is really an extension of the idea of literate programming, basically the idea of

00:58:47.351 --> 00:58:52.991
writing out program logic in a human language with included code snippets and macros.

00:58:52.991 --> 00:58:57.591
So if we look at a plain text document like we have here on the page or a QMD, we have

00:58:57.591 --> 00:59:00.390
the title, which is highlighted here in purple.

00:59:00.390 --> 00:59:04.591
That's the YAML and all the different metadata about the document.

00:59:04.591 --> 00:59:09.790
We have yellow or kind of this off pink here that is highlighting the air quality, the

00:59:09.790 --> 00:59:12.910
relationship between temperature and ozone level, basically the markdown that you're

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:14.191
working on.

00:59:14.191 --> 00:59:19.390
And then the code, which is highlighted here by the R chunk, and it has a label of figure

00:59:19.390 --> 00:59:24.150
air quality, as well as some code to generate a graphic via ggplot.

00:59:24.150 --> 00:59:29.991
So this idea of literate programming allows us to build up different components and write

00:59:29.991 --> 00:59:35.630
out the document as you'd like in real time in a linear way, like top to bottom, but structure

00:59:35.630 --> 00:59:42.231
it and add up all of the actual literate part in additional to the code that you're writing.

00:59:42.231 --> 00:59:46.871
So first we'll kick off with metadata or that YAML that's at the top.

00:59:46.871 --> 00:59:51.071
Metadata or what's called YAML, you could say it's yet another markup language or YAML

00:59:51.071 --> 00:59:53.591
and markup language or whatever you want to say.

00:59:53.591 --> 00:59:57.351
It follows the structure of these key value pairs.

00:59:57.351 --> 01:00:01.550
So you have a key, something like title, and then you have the value you're inputting,

01:00:01.550 --> 01:00:06.351
something like this is my first Quarto document, and you're putting that in as text.

01:00:06.351 --> 01:00:11.831
That's the general structure that all the YAML will follow of just matching some option

01:00:11.831 --> 01:00:14.711
with what the option you've chosen.

01:00:14.711 --> 01:00:19.390
So we think about like output options, going to the next slide, we have format is something.

01:00:19.390 --> 01:00:24.591
So format is the keyword that's saying this is the format we're choosing to render to,

01:00:24.591 --> 01:00:27.231
and the value is something we're choosing.

01:00:27.231 --> 01:00:31.430
Now we're not going to say something, we're going to choose something like HTML or PDF,

01:00:31.430 --> 01:00:37.430
or for today's slides, I used reveal.js to create these interactive HTML slides that

01:00:37.430 --> 01:00:39.351
allow me to step through it.

01:00:39.351 --> 01:00:43.111
And again, it's available through open source.

01:00:43.111 --> 01:00:45.910
So it's not something else I have to install or something else I have to buy.

01:00:45.910 --> 01:00:51.731
It's all built into that as a different format.

01:00:51.731 --> 01:00:55.390
You can also add option arguments or kind of sub commands to this.

01:00:55.390 --> 01:00:59.351
So I'm not limited to just saying HTML, and then I'm done for the day.

01:00:59.351 --> 01:01:04.711
I could say I have a format, and then I go down to a new line, and I have HTML.

01:01:04.711 --> 01:01:08.591
And then on the next line, I have table of contents equals true and code folding equals

01:01:08.591 --> 01:01:09.591
true.

01:01:09.591 --> 01:01:15.471
So again, I can control the structure, control the options within my format by adding these

01:01:15.471 --> 01:01:19.071
sub options to it.

01:01:19.071 --> 01:01:20.910
Sub options are going to be below.

01:01:20.910 --> 01:01:25.591
This is slightly cut off in terms of if you click F, Rachel, it'll go full screen for

01:01:25.591 --> 01:01:27.591
you.

01:01:27.591 --> 01:01:31.711
So it's going to have the sub options of option one and option two.

01:01:31.711 --> 01:01:36.390
The options are not limited to just plain text or just, you know, logicals like true

01:01:36.390 --> 01:01:39.050
and false, but they can be a mixing and matching.

01:01:39.050 --> 01:01:43.311
So some options might be logicals like true, false, or other.

01:01:43.311 --> 01:01:46.311
Some might be text where you're having to quote it, and that's okay.

01:01:46.311 --> 01:01:51.390
It's just depending upon what the options are that you're editing.

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:58.150
Now as far as why you would actually choose YAML is that you might need to avoid mainly

01:01:58.150 --> 01:02:00.550
typing out all these different options.

01:02:00.550 --> 01:02:04.951
You know, if I just have a document like we showed in RStudio Cloud, it's pretty easy

01:02:04.951 --> 01:02:07.550
to say Kordo render document to HTML.

01:02:07.550 --> 01:02:08.550
Yep.

01:02:08.550 --> 01:02:09.550
I got that.

01:02:09.550 --> 01:02:13.150
That's easy enough where I can have fun with it and change it around.

01:02:13.150 --> 01:02:17.750
But if I wanted to start adding additional things, I can do those via the command line,

01:02:17.750 --> 01:02:23.030
but it gets a bit tricky in terms of like Kordo render document to HTML, add some options

01:02:23.030 --> 01:02:25.750
where code and folding is equal to true.

01:02:25.750 --> 01:02:27.111
Not too bad.

01:02:27.111 --> 01:02:30.951
But then I have something really long, and I have this like Kordo render document with

01:02:30.951 --> 01:02:34.410
code folding parameters, and it's running off the page.

01:02:34.410 --> 01:02:35.811
It's too long.

01:02:35.811 --> 01:02:39.770
So while you can absolutely use that, maybe you have it in like continuous integration

01:02:39.851 --> 01:02:41.811
or something else.

01:02:41.811 --> 01:02:47.010
It's much easier to write this via YAML, and that's why the YAML is provided is to structure

01:02:47.010 --> 01:02:50.851
these different options.

01:02:50.851 --> 01:02:56.851
Now as far as navigating within RStudio, I might walk again, Rachel, through this in

01:02:56.851 --> 01:02:57.851
RStudio Cloud.

01:02:57.851 --> 01:03:01.971
If you want to click escape, it'll get you out of full screen, and then you go back to

01:03:01.971 --> 01:03:04.351
RStudio Cloud.

01:03:04.351 --> 01:03:07.731
For anyone that missed this before, I just want to point out where the console and where

01:03:07.731 --> 01:03:09.591
the terminal is.

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:14.910
So at the bottom left, we have the R console where you execute R code or you load packages

01:03:14.910 --> 01:03:17.091
or whatever else you want to do.

01:03:17.091 --> 01:03:21.991
And then right next to it on the tab is a word called terminal.

01:03:21.991 --> 01:03:27.390
And so if you click on terminal next to console on the bottom left, now you're at a command

01:03:27.390 --> 01:03:32.351
line interface or at the terminal inside RStudio Cloud, although it might be organized a bit

01:03:32.351 --> 01:03:34.991
differently on your specific computer.

01:03:34.991 --> 01:03:39.550
That's where you could execute the Cordo command line interface as opposed to the R

01:03:39.550 --> 01:03:45.471
package that would be executed inside the R console or in a .R or .qmd file.

01:03:45.471 --> 01:03:49.170
So just wanted to make sure that we have that differentiation between the terminal exists,

01:03:49.170 --> 01:03:50.871
you can execute code there.

01:03:50.871 --> 01:03:54.831
If you just installed Cordo, you might need to restart RStudio.

01:03:54.831 --> 01:03:58.770
For example, like if you install them separately, or if you're making changes, you typically

01:03:58.770 --> 01:04:02.991
want to refresh to make sure everything's available.

01:04:02.991 --> 01:04:06.430
Let's go back to the slides real quick.

01:04:06.430 --> 01:04:13.191
We've covered the navigation, perfect.

01:04:13.191 --> 01:04:17.951
The other part you might see is that when you click, say, the render button in RStudio,

01:04:17.951 --> 01:04:20.670
it's actually going to open up what's called a background job.

01:04:20.670 --> 01:04:24.270
Now here, rather than Rachel having to go and navigate to RStudio Cloud, I've got a

01:04:24.270 --> 01:04:27.191
screenshot for you.

01:04:27.191 --> 01:04:31.510
It's going to start this and maintain a background job for you.

01:04:31.510 --> 01:04:35.630
Part of why it does this is when you click the render button in RStudio, it both renders

01:04:35.630 --> 01:04:41.910
the document out and then maintains a stateful browser or kind of web server in the background.

01:04:41.910 --> 01:04:47.150
So as you make changes, you can re-render it and get the full thing built up together.

01:04:47.150 --> 01:04:51.670
So this is really useful for things like websites or building out complex structures where you're

01:04:51.670 --> 01:04:56.030
adding a lot of different components and you want to see how they all interact.

01:04:56.030 --> 01:05:01.111
If you did something via the R console, it would actually execute just as it was and

01:05:01.111 --> 01:05:04.150
render out the document without the background job.

01:05:04.150 --> 01:05:08.111
Or if you executed something via the terminal, it would just execute it via the terminal

01:05:08.111 --> 01:05:10.831
and not create a background job.

01:05:10.831 --> 01:05:15.630
But the Cordo render button specifically will start this background job and maintain it

01:05:15.630 --> 01:05:16.991
in the background.

01:05:16.991 --> 01:05:21.471
You could always kill it off or stop it if you wanted to stop that from being rendered

01:05:21.471 --> 01:05:23.711
in the back.

01:05:23.711 --> 01:05:26.270
For today, I saw a couple of questions about the recording.

01:05:26.270 --> 01:05:31.390
So this is on YouTube right now and you can access it in the future via YouTube as well.

01:05:31.390 --> 01:05:36.871
So it'll be both the live version that you're watching right now and the recorded version

01:05:36.871 --> 01:05:41.630
will both live on YouTube at the link you're at right now.

01:05:41.630 --> 01:05:45.550
Again for rendering, if you click that render button, that's where you get the background

01:05:45.550 --> 01:05:46.670
job.

01:05:46.670 --> 01:05:52.670
But you can also call it via the terminal in Cordo render or via the R console via the

01:05:52.670 --> 01:05:56.550
Cordo R package and call them Cordo underscore render.

01:05:56.550 --> 01:05:57.790
So all these are valid.

01:05:57.790 --> 01:06:00.750
There's not really a requirement to do it one way or the other.

01:06:00.750 --> 01:06:03.270
Just part of it is what are you needing to do?

01:06:03.270 --> 01:06:06.591
Like are you trying to render a document to different formats?

01:06:06.591 --> 01:06:12.030
You could do that very easily via the terminal or the R package without having to modify

01:06:12.030 --> 01:06:12.871
the document.

