01:39:19.498 --> 01:39:24.598
I have rmarkdown documents and I want to render them as is to Quarto.

01:39:24.598 --> 01:39:28.298
I was like what all do I have to change? Do I have to change a lot of things?

01:39:28.298 --> 01:39:33.758
Rachel, did you have a question? Sorry. I noticed there was a question that's been asked a few times, so I just wanted to ask it.

01:39:33.758 --> 01:39:38.538
Is there a shortcut for the hash pipe?

01:39:38.538 --> 01:39:47.198
I don't think there is, but if you type one hash pipe and click enter, it will automatically add those below them.

01:39:47.198 --> 01:39:53.058
So basically, once you've inserted one hash pipe, as you go to more chunk options, it will automatically insert

01:39:53.058 --> 01:39:59.898
the starting structure of the pound sign, the vertical line, and a space for you. Thank you for that question, Rachel.

01:39:59.898 --> 01:40:02.998
Awesome, thanks.

01:40:02.998 --> 01:40:08.457
So for people that say, I have a bunch of rmarkdown documents, I want to

01:40:08.457 --> 01:40:12.257
apply it across different things, or I want to convert them over to Quarto,

01:40:12.257 --> 01:40:16.018
you can generally just render them via the command line.

01:40:16.018 --> 01:40:21.358
So you can call Quarto render on a document and render it and force it to be used via Quarto.

01:40:21.358 --> 01:40:25.718
If you wanted to modify your YAML and make it Quarto specific,

01:40:25.718 --> 01:40:30.358
you could change two primary parts. You change output to format

01:40:30.358 --> 01:40:33.658
and something like HTML document to HTML.

01:40:33.658 --> 01:40:37.658
There are smaller things of things like number underscore sections.

01:40:37.658 --> 01:40:44.218
Rather than using that syntax, we're using Pandoc style or traditional YAML style with a dash.

01:40:44.218 --> 01:40:49.718
But overall, you can see that as you're moving between these documents, that the formats actually look very similar.

01:40:49.718 --> 01:40:53.017
And again, you don't have to convert all of your documents over.

01:40:53.017 --> 01:41:00.517
It's more of like keep the existing documents you have, use something like the Quarto R package or the Quarto command line tool

01:41:00.517 --> 01:41:06.057
to render older rmarkdown documents and then write new documents via Quarto.

01:41:06.057 --> 01:41:13.718
But if you wanted to convert your documents and change all the YAML, you could do it manually as well if you'd like to.

01:41:13.718 --> 01:41:20.818
This is partially off the page, I'm sorry about that, but for the YAML for Quarto, the big important part here is again,

01:41:20.818 --> 01:41:28.718
Quarto is going to have this like word dash word syntax, like we think of number dash sections on line five under Quarto,

01:41:28.718 --> 01:41:33.718
as opposed to our markdown is using an underscore for a lot of different things.

01:41:33.718 --> 01:41:39.177
So if you want to be more consistent, that dash syntax is what we're looking for.

01:41:39.177 --> 01:41:45.677
A couple of good questions about rendering like a parent QMD that has rmarkdown files as its children.

01:41:45.677 --> 01:41:50.378
That's a pretty specific thing in terms of you're bringing in code from an rmarkdown file.

01:41:50.378 --> 01:41:57.958
If you're just reading in the lines of code, that's fine because you're not actually rendering it to rmarkdown, you're rendering it to Quarto.

01:41:57.958 --> 01:42:06.458
But if you have to say like a Quarto project or Quarto website, anything that's .RMD within that will actually be rendered via Quarto.

01:42:06.458 --> 01:42:12.617
So you can't like render something to rmarkdown just like out of the box via Quarto.

01:42:12.617 --> 01:42:18.458
It's going to be a Quarto document at that point. It's just going to try its best to convert it over.

01:42:18.458 --> 01:42:23.557
Good question. Within the workshop material, I have what's called like an old rmarkdown.

01:42:23.617 --> 01:42:31.158
Again, without changing anything, I can render it to Quarto by using the Quarto command line interface or the Quarto R package.

01:42:31.158 --> 01:42:38.298
Or I can manually go in and change .RMD to .QMD, and that indicates, hey, use Quarto.

01:42:38.298 --> 01:42:45.298
Or I could change the format from output to format to convert it over via the YAML header itself.

01:42:46.298 --> 01:42:54.298
Now, as far as this conversion process, well, again, it's not required, and many times you can kind of render something as is.

01:42:54.298 --> 01:43:02.298
Option one is I want an rmarkdown, I want to always use Quarto for the rendering, change just .RMD to .QMD.

01:43:02.298 --> 01:43:08.298
That tells RStudio and that tells Quarto, this is a Quarto document, render it as Quarto.

01:43:08.298 --> 01:43:13.298
So it'll force it to be executed as a Quarto document, no matter what is in the YAML.

01:43:14.298 --> 01:43:23.298
Option two is you can manually change the output, like output equals HTML document to something like format equals HTML.

01:43:23.298 --> 01:43:29.298
And again, this will force using Quarto, even if the extension is .RMD.

01:43:31.298 --> 01:43:40.297
The last option, though, here is, you know, you've got a rendering to Quarto, but maybe your knitter chunks, your code chunks are different.

01:43:40.297 --> 01:43:52.297
So there is a function in the dev version of Knitter, as of a couple days ago, that allows you to take syntax like fig.width equals one.

01:43:52.297 --> 01:43:54.297
I think we actually have to click through twice on that, sorry.

01:43:56.297 --> 01:44:01.297
One more time, there we go. So fig.width equals one, and it'll convert it over to the hashpipe syntax.

01:44:01.297 --> 01:44:09.297
So that'll allow you to take an entire document and very quickly convert all of the Knitter syntax over to the newer syntax.

01:44:09.297 --> 01:44:11.297
I wouldn't necessarily use this like all the time.

01:44:11.297 --> 01:44:15.297
I'd rather just write them as they're supposed to be moving forward.

01:44:15.297 --> 01:44:21.297
But if you have older documents, this would allow you to convert the chunk header into the hashpipe syntax.

01:44:24.297 --> 01:44:27.297
Again, you don't have to convert everything.

01:44:27.297 --> 01:44:30.297
It's backward compatible with the older chunk options.

01:44:31.297 --> 01:44:37.297
But if you want to be consistent or you want to kind of move towards a syntax that allows you to be more consistent moving forward.

01:44:40.297 --> 01:44:54.297
The other part was, you know, we talked quite a bit about this fence div or these Pandoc divs and something like the colon, colon, colon, curly brackets, layout, or layout number of rows or number of columns.

01:44:54.297 --> 01:45:00.297
Again, we're getting consistency here between something you can do in Markdown, as well as something you can do with code.

01:45:00.297 --> 01:45:08.297
So if we click through this twice, we're going to have the code and then we're going to highlight line four.

01:45:08.297 --> 01:45:16.297
Layout number of column equals two is the exact same syntax I use for fence divs to typeset images.

01:45:16.297 --> 01:45:20.297
But now I'm using it for generated graphics in R.

01:45:20.297 --> 01:45:29.297
So I can get side by side images, obviously on this presentation, because it's in horizontal landscape mode, they're kind of running off the page.

01:45:29.297 --> 01:45:38.297
But on a larger document or a more traditional portrait page, I would have two side by side images and the layout structure will look nice there.

01:45:40.297 --> 01:45:45.297
I can also use the online seven by click through one more time here.

01:45:45.297 --> 01:45:48.297
I get layout and I have that again, percentage style.

01:45:48.297 --> 01:45:56.297
So now I have 40 percent for image one, 40 percent for image two and negative 20 percent of blank space in the middle.

01:45:57.297 --> 01:46:07.297
And when I do this, it's generating, again, two graphics with blank space in the middle and also applying the figure caption and the labeling of those in my entire document.

01:46:07.297 --> 01:46:19.297
So a nice ability to, again, have consistent syntax of typesetting and arranging your documents, whether it's bringing in raw graphics off disk or generating graphics on the fly in R or Python or Julia.

