01:53:05.297 --> 01:53:13.297
So Cordo projects, number one, are directories that provide a way to render all or some of the files in a directory with a single command,

01:53:13.297 --> 01:53:17.297
something like Cordo render my project.

01:53:17.297 --> 01:53:27.297
Another one might be a way to share YAML configuration across multiple documents in terms of rather than writing a bunch of YAML for individual documents over and over,

01:53:27.297 --> 01:53:36.297
I can use a Cordo project to apply the same YAML to an entire directory of five or 10 or even dozens or hundreds of documents.

01:53:36.297 --> 01:53:39.297
It also allows me to control where documents are rendered to.

01:53:39.297 --> 01:53:49.297
So I can redirect my artifacts out to a separate directory and have a clean directory of experimentation and then the actual final output to a separate directory.

01:53:49.297 --> 01:53:56.297
And most importantly, I think, for things like blogs or other complex sites is I can freeze rendered output.

01:53:56.297 --> 01:54:05.297
So you can imagine that I have a blog post from four years ago using some code with a package that may not even exist anymore.

01:54:05.297 --> 01:54:11.297
Rather than having to re-execute that four-year-old blog post every time I render my blog or my website,

01:54:11.297 --> 01:54:15.297
it will actually store the computation and freeze that output for me.

01:54:15.297 --> 01:54:22.297
So when I render everything else, it just renders the new thing or the things I'm telling it to render.

01:54:22.297 --> 01:54:26.297
And in addition, projects allow you to create essentially aggregations.

01:54:26.297 --> 01:54:36.297
So you can imagine a book or a website is really just multiple Cordo documents or HTML pages or PDF pages that are combined into a single output.

01:54:36.297 --> 01:54:43.297
So just like the website for accessing the content you found today or a book or anything else you're publishing,

01:54:43.297 --> 01:54:49.297
you can create much more complex things by using Cordo projects.

01:54:49.297 --> 01:54:54.297
For what a Cordo project looks like, you might have a minimal one that looks something like this.

01:54:54.297 --> 01:54:59.297
It's always going to be created with a underscore Cordo.yaml file.

01:54:59.297 --> 01:55:05.297
That is always what the file is called to create a Cordo project, underscore Cordo.yaml.

01:55:05.297 --> 01:55:10.297
And that will affect everything in its directory and subdirectories of it.

01:55:10.297 --> 01:55:14.297
So for number one within the Cordo.yaml, it's a project.

01:55:14.297 --> 01:55:16.297
And we're not saying it's a website or it's a book.

01:55:16.297 --> 01:55:24.297
We're just saying this is a Cordo project and I want you to take everything I create and throw them into this underscore output folder.

01:55:24.297 --> 01:55:27.297
And I can apply some YAML across all of them.

01:55:27.297 --> 01:55:30.297
I want Table of Contents to always be true on a number of sections.

01:55:30.297 --> 01:55:34.297
And I have a bibliography that I want to bring in for all of my citations.

01:55:34.297 --> 01:55:39.297
Then I can also say that I'm creating these in both HTML and PDF at the same time.

01:55:40.297 --> 01:55:46.297
So for my HTML, I can apply custom styling with CSS and use a specific math method.

01:55:46.297 --> 01:55:51.297
And then for PDF, I want to create a report and customize the overall layout.

01:55:51.297 --> 01:55:57.297
So it allows you to kind of structure all these different things, create a new output directory with all the files that you're rendering.

01:55:57.297 --> 01:56:05.297
And it could, again, be many, many files and control it for different syntaxes in HTML and PDF.

