02:02:08.298 --> 02:02:10.298
Yeah, absolutely.

02:02:10.298 --> 02:02:12.298
There it is.

02:02:12.298 --> 02:02:19.298
What this whole section covers is essentially that idea of I want to freeze or control execution.

02:02:19.298 --> 02:02:23.298
And you can do that with or without virtual environments.

02:02:23.298 --> 02:02:25.298
So we're going to put a side by side real quick.

02:02:25.298 --> 02:02:29.298
So on this page, it talks about just the general idea of managing execution.

02:02:29.298 --> 02:02:42.298
So if you scroll down to freeze, you can use freeze to basically say, I want you to freeze the output of code, meaning that even if someone else tries to render it, it's not going to re-execute the code.

02:02:42.298 --> 02:02:46.298
They don't even have to have Python installed on their machine or are installed on the machine.

02:02:46.298 --> 02:02:52.298
It's just going to be rendering the HTML or the PDF via Cordo.

02:02:52.298 --> 02:02:57.298
If you have freeze equals false, then it will always try and re-execute code.

02:02:57.298 --> 02:03:10.298
But freeze equals true or freeze equals auto allows you to say only re-execute code when I change the source code or just never do it unless I manually force click render on that document.

02:03:10.298 --> 02:03:18.298
If you go down one section lower, there's using freeze and then one more subsection, virtual environments.

02:03:18.298 --> 02:03:26.298
It talks about that you might have a requirements.txt or a virtual environment like a venv in Python or an renv in R.

02:03:26.298 --> 02:03:29.298
Again, we're not doing a special language.

02:03:29.298 --> 02:03:32.298
It's whatever you're using in another language is what you use.

02:03:32.298 --> 02:03:50.298
I most commonly use venv in virtualenv in Python, and I'm using renv in R to control exactly installing specific libraries or a collection of libraries and defining those into a virtual environment.

