02:05:47.298 --> 02:05:48.298
Yep.

02:05:48.298 --> 02:05:55.298
So if you had a presentation like I had in reveal.js, the images are going to be stacked on top of each other.

02:05:55.298 --> 02:05:57.298
It's not going to try to align them automatically.

02:05:57.298 --> 02:06:01.298
It's just going to pull them to the left and inject them one on top of the other.

02:06:01.298 --> 02:06:11.298
You can use something like the dot columns, fence divs, to put them side by side, almost like Rachel and I are left aligned and right aligned right now in two columns.

02:06:11.298 --> 02:06:28.298
Or you could use absolute positioning with graphics and you could do a dot absolute class and then say literally from the top or the left or the right or the bottom of the screen, put them 150 pixels to the left and 200 pixels up.

02:06:28.298 --> 02:06:33.298
I would probably not put them inside bullets unless you had really small images.

02:06:33.298 --> 02:06:46.298
You could do icons with like font awesome if they're really small, but generally I would rely on alignment with the more typical fence divs that we showed in today's presentation.

02:06:46.298 --> 02:06:47.298
Great, thank you.

02:06:47.298 --> 02:06:54.298
