02:12:58.143 --> 02:13:01.703
Do I love Hugo, or do I not love Hugo?

02:13:01.703 --> 02:13:04.742
Hugo is the rendering engine that BlogDown uses.

02:13:04.742 --> 02:13:06.703
So when you're actually using BlogDown,

02:13:06.703 --> 02:13:10.343
you're writing .rmds or .rmarkdown files

02:13:10.343 --> 02:13:12.463
that generate .md files.

02:13:12.463 --> 02:13:15.082
And then you hand over everything to Hugo

02:13:15.082 --> 02:13:18.262
to render it and create HTML.

02:13:18.262 --> 02:13:20.383
That is really powerful for creating

02:13:20.383 --> 02:13:24.543
exceptionally complex and specific websites.

02:13:24.543 --> 02:13:26.003
I can think of some of the websites

02:13:26.003 --> 02:13:27.742
I've seen that people like Allison Hill

02:13:27.742 --> 02:13:30.043
has created that are just beautiful and very

02:13:30.043 --> 02:13:32.562
functional and amazing.

02:13:32.562 --> 02:13:35.723
I am a noted Hugo non-fan.

02:13:35.723 --> 02:13:39.922
Whatever the opposite of a stan is, I am not a stan of Hugo.

02:13:39.922 --> 02:13:42.403
It's a separate thing that I have to manage.

02:13:42.403 --> 02:13:44.363
The BlogDown team has done a lot of work

02:13:44.363 --> 02:13:46.803
to make it much more user-friendly.

02:13:46.803 --> 02:13:49.443
But for me, it just was not the right option.

02:13:49.443 --> 02:13:51.503
It was not something I loved.

02:13:51.503 --> 02:13:53.323
If you have a very complex workflow

02:13:53.323 --> 02:13:55.202
and BlogDown's working for you, again, we're

02:13:55.202 --> 02:13:57.382
going to maintain BlogDown.

02:13:57.403 --> 02:14:01.403
And you can technically write Hugo-style Markdown documents

02:14:01.403 --> 02:14:02.782
with Cordo.

02:14:02.782 --> 02:14:05.683
Some of the things you lose by using

02:14:05.683 --> 02:14:09.922
Hugo as your rendering engine is things like interactivity,

02:14:09.922 --> 02:14:12.922
because you're only writing out that md that then gets parsed

02:14:12.922 --> 02:14:16.323
by Hugo, is you're always going to be limited in the things you

02:14:16.323 --> 02:14:18.683
can do with HTML widgets or Jupyter widgets

02:14:18.683 --> 02:14:22.842
or Observable because you're writing plain text.

02:14:22.842 --> 02:14:25.323
But BlogDown's very, very efficient at rendering

02:14:25.323 --> 02:14:26.963
1,000 blog posts.

02:14:26.982 --> 02:14:29.223
And I know for some people, like Yiwei,

02:14:29.223 --> 02:14:32.263
he literally has a blog that's been going for 15 years

02:14:32.263 --> 02:14:34.903
and has thousands of blog posts.

02:14:34.903 --> 02:14:38.702
For him, the conversion cost doesn't make any sense.

02:14:38.702 --> 02:14:40.223
His blog is working great.

02:14:40.223 --> 02:14:41.583
We're maintaining BlogDown.

02:14:41.583 --> 02:14:43.422
He's actually the maintainer of BlogDown,

02:14:43.422 --> 02:14:45.422
so he knows it's not going away.

02:14:45.422 --> 02:14:47.743
So you don't have to, but I personally

02:14:47.743 --> 02:14:51.943
switched over to using Cordo blogs from Distill.

02:14:51.943 --> 02:14:53.663
So if you're coming from the Distill land,

02:14:53.663 --> 02:14:55.902
I would say there's a much stronger emphasis

02:14:55.902 --> 02:14:58.182
that Cordo brings a lot to the table

02:14:58.182 --> 02:15:03.122
that you're familiar with with Distill, but does it better.

