Edgar Ruiz, part of the team here at our studio,

02:16:40.143 --> 02:16:42.702
is working on a package called Ecodown, which

02:16:42.702 --> 02:16:46.363
allows you to write essentially complex websites that

02:16:46.363 --> 02:16:48.822
encompass multiple packages with Cordo

02:16:48.863 --> 02:16:53.502
and using that as an extension of more of Packagedown.

02:16:53.502 --> 02:16:55.463
I'll have to look at specifically for package

02:16:55.463 --> 02:16:58.183
vignettes as PDF via Cordo.

02:16:58.183 --> 02:17:02.262
But again, you're not really getting like the thing

02:17:02.262 --> 02:17:04.743
you're doing is you're building for CRAN as opposed

02:17:04.743 --> 02:17:06.623
to building for anyone.

02:17:06.623 --> 02:17:08.662
And because there's limitations and a focus

02:17:08.662 --> 02:17:11.822
on what CRAN accepts, all the things you can do in Cordo

02:17:11.822 --> 02:17:14.542
are not necessarily accepted by what CRAN will accept for you.

02:17:15.542 --> 02:17:16.023
OK.

02:17:16.023 --> 02:17:16.783
I lied.

02:17:16.783 --> 02:17:20.743
There's one more question that I'm going to ask right now, too.

02:17:20.743 --> 02:17:23.542
What recommendations do you have for people who are just

02:17:23.542 --> 02:17:24.702
learning about Cordo?

02:17:24.702 --> 02:17:25.942
How should they start?

02:17:25.942 --> 02:17:29.303
And what are the best resources?

02:17:29.303 --> 02:17:30.343
Just do things.

02:17:30.343 --> 02:17:33.743
I mean, that's a trivial answer in terms of like,

02:17:33.743 --> 02:17:34.583
that's not fair.

02:17:34.583 --> 02:17:37.063
But really, it is just do things.

02:17:37.063 --> 02:17:39.743
If you are creating HTML documents,

02:17:39.743 --> 02:17:43.502
and if you stick to very simple HTML documents,

02:17:43.502 --> 02:17:46.822
if you stick to very basic YAML, like literally like format

02:17:46.822 --> 02:17:50.623
equals HTML, format equals PDF, just

02:17:50.623 --> 02:17:53.343
start doing some of your daily work there in terms of rather

02:17:53.343 --> 02:17:56.222
than thinking about, I wrote some .R files.

02:17:56.222 --> 02:17:58.063
I generated a CSV.

02:17:58.063 --> 02:18:00.942
I take the CSV and hand it off to a colleague,

02:18:00.942 --> 02:18:05.023
or I take it into Excel, or I take it into something else.

02:18:05.023 --> 02:18:08.343
Think about what value does Cordo bring to me?

02:18:08.343 --> 02:18:10.542
That ability to mix code that generates

02:18:10.542 --> 02:18:12.702
graphics and tables and text.

02:18:12.702 --> 02:18:15.303
Things like lab notebooks or lab reports,

02:18:15.303 --> 02:18:18.982
or even for like within an organization,

02:18:18.982 --> 02:18:21.662
like generating presentations with code and graphics

02:18:21.662 --> 02:18:23.903
and not having to manually rebuild them,

02:18:23.903 --> 02:18:25.623
or even just normal reports.

02:18:25.623 --> 02:18:27.422
Like, I got a lot of value out of that

02:18:27.422 --> 02:18:30.382
during my PhD using things like R Markdown

02:18:30.382 --> 02:18:33.542
that I may continue to get value out of with Cordo.

02:18:33.542 --> 02:18:35.743
If you really are thinking like, I just want to learn

02:18:35.743 --> 02:18:39.143
and like really learn deeply, Cordo.org

02:18:39.143 --> 02:18:41.023
has the guides.

02:18:41.023 --> 02:18:42.942
Focus, again, on the subset of topics

02:18:42.942 --> 02:18:44.343
that you're trying to learn about.

02:18:44.343 --> 02:18:46.743
Maybe it's presentations and static reports.

02:18:46.743 --> 02:18:48.903
That's a really great place to start.

02:18:48.903 --> 02:18:51.783
And there's a lot of powerful things you can do there.

02:18:51.783 --> 02:18:55.463
So on the left, there's documents and presentations.

02:18:55.463 --> 02:18:57.583
If you just focus on those two tabs,

02:18:57.583 --> 02:19:01.542
you can be very powerful and get a lot of stuff done.

02:19:01.542 --> 02:19:06.183
The other part is the authoring section at the very top.

02:19:06.183 --> 02:19:08.063
That gives you basically what is all

02:19:08.063 --> 02:19:10.542
the Cordo-specific cool stuff I can do.

02:19:10.542 --> 02:19:13.343
And again, most of that is format agnostic,

02:19:13.343 --> 02:19:16.463
as opposed to learning just a specific format.

02:19:16.463 --> 02:19:20.422
So laying tables or graphics or diagrams or whatever else,

02:19:20.422 --> 02:19:22.222
you can write out a lot of different things

02:19:22.222 --> 02:19:24.422
about what's possible in Cordo.

02:19:24.422 --> 02:19:27.783
The last thing I'll say is come to Isabella Velasquez's

02:19:27.783 --> 02:19:28.903
presentation.

02:19:28.903 --> 02:19:31.183
She'll be talking about building a blog.

02:19:31.183 --> 02:19:35.023
Maintaining a personal blog as basically a portfolio

02:19:35.023 --> 02:19:38.702
is useful for you to learn things and share that knowledge

02:19:38.702 --> 02:19:42.382
as well as actually use it in practice.

02:19:42.382 --> 02:19:44.702
And then if you're looking for your next job

02:19:44.702 --> 02:19:47.023
or you're just trying to remember what the heck you did

02:19:47.023 --> 02:19:49.463
six months ago, rather than digging back through notes,

02:19:49.463 --> 02:19:51.063
you can be like, oh, yeah, I literally

02:19:51.063 --> 02:19:52.822
have a blog post about that.

02:19:52.822 --> 02:19:55.783
So I personally, every time I'm trying to figure out, OK,

02:19:55.783 --> 02:19:58.702
how do I scrape JSON data from this website

02:19:58.702 --> 02:20:00.502
and bring it in and plot it?

02:20:00.502 --> 02:20:02.942
I wrote a blog post a year and a half ago

02:20:02.942 --> 02:20:04.502
that tells me how to do that.

02:20:04.502 --> 02:20:06.463
And I don't have to store it all in my head.

02:20:06.463 --> 02:20:10.422
I can use the reference material I wrote for myself.

02:20:10.422 --> 02:20:11.143
That's great.

02:20:11.143 --> 02:20:11.982
